segments.text: The fall of 1944, when you and many of your classmates knew you were going on active duty, did you all still take your academics seriously?
Not as seriously as we probably should.
Some did.
Some of the young ones particularly, you know, I don't know.
But you did go to class every day?
We did go to class.
I always went to class.
It was the easiest way to get by.
I mean, I have a good memory.
I retained what people say, take a couple of notes, and I could come back and do it.
It was just so much easier than trying to dig it up on your own and have the professor tell you, and learn from the professor.
Now, had you already officially joined the Marine Corps?
Second semester, yes.
Second semester.
Second semester.
August, just when the first semester was over in August, I joined the Corps.
All right, and you volunteered for the Marine Corps because of your brother.
Because of my brother.
He's a historian, and you're a historian.
I'm a multiple selection guy.
A, my brother.
B, I don't like cold weather, and I knew that the Europe was cold.
C, I didn't want to wear wool next to my skin, and I knew the Army would make you wear wool shirts next to your skin.
D,
I'd rather kill a Jap than kill a blond-headed, blue-eyed German who might be my cousin.

My father knew people at the replacement, or the drives where you first went in down in San Antonio, and I had a cousin that went through there and went into OCS, and everybody said my father did it for him.
And if I did anything, I wanted to do it in my own name and not have my father get credit for it as then a lieutenant colonel in the Army.
So I'm of multiple causes.
Why did I do it?
I wanted to replace my brother.
I wanted to kill jobs.
I wanted to, if I had to kill anybody, I didn't want to go into, I didn't want to get my feet cold and get frostbite and stuff like that.
So all those reasons are there.
I'm from Orange County.
And the Kishi family, which produced a number of Aggies, some of whom were real World War II heroes, were there any Japanese-American students at A&M?
I don't remember seeing them.
I've never heard of any during the war.
I've never heard of them.
Right.
That fall, you're still treated as fish, and so you still have to clean things up.
Yeah.
and there were run details, and there were yell practices, but you all did not march into the game.
After the game, when the Aggies won, did you still throw the yell leaders into the pond?
I don't remember doing that.
I don't remember doing that.
I don't remember the pond, as a matter of fact.
Did many people come to the games?
No.
Because gas was tough.
Gas was tough.
If they ever got 38,000 there, it was a huge, big crowd.
And sometimes they came on the train?
Oh, yeah.
And the big thing that's changed for that whole era is going to the game was a social event.
Men wore jackets and ties, and women wore dresses and corsages and silk stockings and silk hose.
And all the games were day games.
And all the games were day games.
And it was a time to get together in the YMCA.
You couldn't get through the YMCA hardly at all.
It was crowded.
Crowded.
And so it was a good experience.
Did anybody take any strong drinks to games?
Oh, yes.
Much more.
drunkenness in those days than there is today.
Where did Aggies buy their drinks?
Neither my father, mother, nor I drank.
So I don't know.
They just had them.
There were a lot of advertising lights stopped outside of Waco to get beer and so forth.
I know that Austin was the smallest town where you could buy, where they had a university where you could buy beer.
And all the games were day games.
All the games were day games, and the band was there.
Did you go on court trips during the war?
Yeah, hitchhiking.
One of them, a friend of mine, we had a walk-on quarterback from Plainview taking in Bob Horn.
They went to Naval Academy and started a quarterback there in the fall of 1949.
And Bob Lane, my roommate and I, were hitching, and
our suitemates from Hearn came by and they had a two-seat coupe.
And they said, well, if we would ride the truck, and if we would go by to see Hearn play Franklin on Friday night, they would take us to Dallas in the coupe, in the trunk of the coupe.
We said, that's a deal.
And we got in the trunk of the coupe and drove up to Franklin and saw the Hearn-Franklin football game and got back in it.
And we put a two-by-four to hold it back.
They lived openly.

Well, we hit a bump, and the two-by-four went flying, and the lid came down, and it wasn't dangerous or anything like that, but the guy driving the car named Lawson or Cornforth, kind of gigantic pull-in for guys, he pulled in and told the attendant to check his spare tire, you know, and the attendant opened it, and it was three bodies, and all of them were pretty big guys, and he opened that thing, and there were three bodies, and he jumped back,
But we drove up to Ornby and saw the game at Ornby Stadium.
And yeah, we went on court trips.
And of course, you know, I'm sure you write and meet the girls from TSCW there in Dallas at the court trips.
And one time I met a very fine girl there named Pam Burgess, who had apparently a skill, a pretty good pianist.
She had played in Boston and going
She played in the Governor's Mansion.
And when I say this, there's nothing of color in any of this.
The thing I would say about A&M then and A&M today, the surface morality was much higher then than it is now.
But the spirituality is much greater now than it was then.
There was much more real commitment today to spiritual things than there was then.
It was a kind of a surface.
Everybody is Christian.
There's a Christian country, so you're born into Christianity, cultural rather than personal.
And on those court trips, as you all marched down the street and so forth, how did the observers respond?
a very patriotic era.
Later on, I knew a mother who said she always wanted her son to come to A&M.
She had two sons that went to Baylor, and they were athletes.
And her third son came to A&M, and she was thrilled that he didn't go to Baylor.
They were from Waco.
And he's an athlete called for him at A&M now.
And she wanted, because it was patriotic.
And everybody in the 30s in that time, well by the time I got here of course we were in the war, but in the 30s everybody knew we were going to soon be in war.
And the advantage of A&M also at that time was getting the reserve commission gave you an extra degree of economic security.
When my dad was on CC duty, we knew a lot of graduate engineers.
who until they were called active duty were pumping gas to put money into the family.
They were just literally out there and servicing cars, changing oil and things like that as graduate engineers.
But they were called active duty as lieutenants and captains.
And it was another security element for them.
And A&M grew in enrollment.
The golden years of A&M in many ways was that
late 1930s with the war coming on and the Depression and cheap education.
Describe, if you can, that fall semester or the summer, first Silver Taps and then Bonfire as it was held then in those days.
Silver Taps was held whenever any one individual was killed, died, or something.
And it was very similar to what they do today, except probably just as somber and

you know, and the one thing that I pictured as different is they had the silver taps from the top of the academic building and then another one further away and then another one further away, so you've got an echo effect.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
It was very, very, very, much more moving than it is today, because they'd play, this one would start and then this one would start and then that one would start.
You'd turn out all the lights and things like that, and we'd all march, we would
March down there, it was something you would go to.
Did anybody not take it seriously?
Nothing, no.
No pranks?
No pranks.
And when you got back to the dorm, appropriate seriousness?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
I don't recall any, and if somebody said something, I mean, I'm not saying, I just don't.
I've never heard of any.
Now, Bonfire was in the drill field, and we'd go out, and we'd cut the logs,
We had no moving equipment, except trucks.
Were there some logs in 44?
Yeah.
Oh, really?
Yeah, we'd go out and cut the logs.
And my shoulders got scraped and everything else.
We'd hold them on our shoulders, carry them to the truck, put them on the truck.
The truck would bring them here, and then we would bring them in.
And it's just a TP effect, one layer.
About how long chronologically did you all work on the bonfire?
A week, a month?
I'd say a week and 10 days.
Not that long.
All right.
And so they had quit by 1944.
They had quit putting trash wood.
Yeah.
There was some trash on it, but basically it was a teepee effect of trees.
Of logs.
Because, see, in the late 30s, they used quite often the wood crating and so forth from the railroad.
Right.
It was a burning up of trash.
Yeah.
All right.
So it's held on the drill.
But the thing is that we did not have a crange to lift up.
Yeah.
all that stuff.
We don't understand why they can't go back to that.
It was relatively safe.
Who did the cutting?
Freshmen.
Freshmen.
I think we did, but I know we did the carrot.
And you used two-man saws?
Yeah, and axes.
And axes.
Do you remember any injuries?
No, except scratch on Ray's shoulders.
But nobody got a leg cut off or a hand or anything like that?
There ain't no power saws.
Did anybody attempt any kind of pranks, any outsider, with Bonfire?
What year was that that the Texas tribe had come over?
Oh, no, that's later.
That's later.
That's the only thing I remember, no.
It would have been worth somebody's life if we were friends.
I mean, it was... What were you all told that Bonfire symbolized?
What did it represent?
We didn't make a big deal out of it, really.
Nothing.
Was there much of a crowd?
A long time.
No, I mean, just cadets.
All right, then you go home at the end of the semester, which would have been late January.
Well, I didn't go home.
See, I went to the Marines.
No, but the semester is over, and you reported for active duty.
Yeah, active duty to the Marines.
All right, briefly summarize your active duty service.
Okay, I went to the Marines, and they gave me the...

responsibility of getting about six guys from San Antonio to Atlanta, Georgia with an eight day, eight hour layover in New Orleans and I sweated that one out getting back on that train in New Orleans.
I went to Atlanta.
In Atlanta they put us on another train.
I lost my responsibility and my authority and became another Munich and we went to Parris Island and there they put us on
cattle cars, bus, semi-trucks, and drove us in to Parris Island, where we were met by a legend in the Marine Corps in World War II, covered in Time magazine, Sergeant Lou Diamond.
And he was a goatee to the guy, using all kinds of profanity and everything else.
I was six feet three, weighed about 155 pounds, and was in excellent shape from my freshman year at A&M, from running mile and seven-tenths and other things that we did here.
And...

The biggest adjustment I had in boot camp was I was taken out of my socioeconomic level, geographic socioeconomic level, and thrown in with a bunch of people that were totally different culturally from me, all the way from an illiterate from Alabama, whom I was supposed to teach the General Orders, and I said, First General, take charge of this post.
When we took charge and I had to try to explain to him, they pulled him out, thank goodness, to people from the scum that scraped off the streets of New York City, real scumbags.
And the language they used was different from what I've been used to.
I never heard the word scum.
The name of Jesus Christ taken as an oath, you know, it was something we, damn hell, a lot of other things, but not, that was not something you would use in the South.
You never heard said that.
I was designated a acting squad leader by, platoon leader, you'll be interested in this, was one Shelby Foote, who had a strange background.
He had been cashiered out of the Army as a captain.
I don't know if you know this about Shelby Foote.
No.
He had something happen in North Ireland.
In the height of the war, he had been booted out of the Army as an uncommissioned officer and was dragged to enlist in the Marines as a private.
I wonder if that's in the standard biography of Foote.
No, I don't think so.
I called him and just talked to him a little bit, you know, after I got my doctorate in history.
But he, and then presumably there were B-12 types who'd been bumped out of B-12 programs or something.
How well prepared had your A&M experience made you for those responsibilities?
Oh, very much so.
Very much so.
Particularly, I gained 30 pounds at Marine Corps boot camp.
Physically, it was very easy.
Psychologically, having to adjust to the new culture was pretty tough.
When I was at Bukank, they called me over and said, we're going to go to second phase.
After second phase, would you be interested in going to Japanese language school, which studies your tests?
And by this time, the romance of the Marine Corps and the adventure had kind of worn off.
And I like to be a student.
I like to go to school.
I love to go to school.
And yeah, I'd be interested in it.
I went to second phase training, which was good.
It was not bad.
And then they asked me to, I had to go before a board to tell them why I wanted to go to Jet League.

And I lied like a trooper and talked my way into it, where apparently a fellow by the name of Robert Bork was there at the same time, because I heard them ask him, where were you when the atomic bomb went off?
And he said, Japanese language school in the Marine Corps in Cancun, June.
And that's where I was.
And very small, so I had to see him.
But we both came to probably 50 pounds since those days.
He wasn't a best friend, don't misunderstand me.
But I didn't know him.
He must have been there.
I must have seen him.
And then after the war was over, as soon as the war was over, I forget that going to Japan and speaking the language.
I said, I want to get out of this.
And so I went.
flunked out of Japanese language school, to put it bluntly.
I didn't try at all.
And so then they sent me to combat intelligence school, then I went to Quantico, rifle range coaching school, I was always, they kept putting me in school.
Then finally, in a brigade, first special marine brigade, we went on maneuvers down off of Puerto Rico, out of Calibra, then on Puerto Rico.
And then they brought us back up on the transport
into New York Harbor, sailed up Hudson River to 125th Street.
And in order to get $300 mustering out pay, rather than $200, you had to be overseas for one month or more.
And they kept us on that boat for 32 days, for two days over a month.
Of those two days, we were on the boat, theoretically.
But we were in New York for eight days.
Four days, they let us have leave.
And then the other two days, they gave us overnight passes.
So out of those eight days, six days was a leave or pass.
And you go into New York and get free tickets to South Pacific, Big Dog Baby, Red Mill, free tickets to baseball games, Yankee baseball games, nickel hot dogs, free Pepsi Cola in Times Square.
I stayed at the Taft Hotel at 42nd Avenue and 7th Avenue and 42nd Street.
7th Avenue and 42nd Street.
And the room was $7 a night.
Vincent Moe plays, playing for your dancing pleasure in the ballroom, $7 a night.
And I remember I...
Got on the subway.
It was an elevator at that point, 125th Street, Old Morrison, Texas.
And I never thought I was on anything going so fast when I went down underground.
You know, it's so close, it's going by.
And I got off at 42nd Street and Broadway, a junction there, and got up and knew where the tagged hotel was.
A fellow from up in that area told me about the tag.
And I walked up to it, got there, and I said, can you tell me where Times Square is?
Because I'd been listening to radio at Little Theater on Times Square and all this thing.
And I figured it was just kind of like Alhambra or like Camelot or something, just a gorgeous, glorious place.
And they said, well, where did you come from?
I said, I got off at Subway right there.
And they said, well, you walked right across it on the way here.
And all I saw was orange juice sales and things like that.
And so it was funny.
And so then I went back to Quantico, Virginia, and waited out until my points built up and got discharged.
And when I was in, and when I was, my wife will get it.
When I was in, for a while I was a transient and had no assigned duties.
And they'd keep us busy.
And I got to be perfect at avoiding that.
We'd fall out about four ranks.
I always get the last rank, have a clipboard, and then call my name.
As soon as they called my name, I'd be all the way here.
I'd step back one step, walk along the formation all the way, very official looking, not try to hide, walk right in front of all the non-coms, and go over to the library and the snag bar.
They were in the same building.
And read and listen to the jukebox and listen to...
Doris Day sang Sentimental Journey and dreamed about getting on that train, counting every mile of railroad track that takes me back to Texas.
But I got to be really good at avoiding these make jobs.
But I didn't get in trouble.
I read trigonometry.
It was a history of Texas government in the West.
It was the first time I heard of John Wesley Hardin.
When I came home, I asked my grandfather,
Paudie, did you ever hear of John Wesley?
Oh, no, I saw him.
And I think he's dead, too.
He said he and his father were coming through, and John Wesley was riding a horse, and his father was driving a wagon that came down to a ford here across the Brazos River.
And there was a deputy sheriff there.
And the deputy sheriff pretended he didn't recognize John Wesley Horton.
And so he didn't try to do anything, and he went peacefully on his way.
Now, was this the Aggie grandfather?
Grandfather, yeah.
Now, did he tell you anything about his attitude when you became an Aggie?
Did he say anything to you about A&M?
The only thing he had said, that if any grandson of his ever became the captain of the Texas A&M football team, he would give them 200 acres of land.
Now, his great-great-grandson started for...
the Aggies in the Cotton Bowl against Auburn.
His name was Wiley.
He was his son's daughter's, his son's, no, his granddaughter's, his son's son's daughter's son.
Randy Wiley started at guard.
under Jackie Sherrill.
But did he ever say to you that it was important to be an Aggie, or really?
He didn't need to.
Okay.
Now, in fact, we, you know, and I talked to, when I was at William & Mary, there was a, I really thought I could have gotten in and get some back here.
Here I was an Aggie.
I was not really proud of my history degree for me.
I knew that I was going to
why I thought this.
And then I had a master's from when I was in the Army from Hardin-Simmons.
And it ended up William and Mary, they were all Ivy Leaguers.
And I walked in and saw John Shelby there.
And I walked in the door and he said, what are you going to write your dissertation on?
What's the topic of your dissertation?
And I didn't even know what he was talking about.
I didn't start talking.
Words that I had not yet formed in my historiography.
And I didn't know how to pronounce it either.
And it was really bad.
They said, go over and see Dr. Brown, Richard Maxwell Brown, over in the library.
And I thought, well, Selby's PhD from Brown.
Brown's PhD from Harvard.
I can't talk to a guy from Brown.
I haven't ever talked to a guy from Harvard.
And I went over there, knocked on the door, came in.
He said, oh, you came from Abilene, Texas.
I said, yeah.
He said, did you ever know him?
high school football player there named Jack Mildred.
Yeah, yeah, you know him.
He showed me another magazine called Texas Full.
He said, I've got every copy that's ever been printed out of the house here.
It turned out he was a big aficionado for Southwest Conference and Texas high school football.
And while I'm talking to him, the phone rings.
He's the expert witness on...
Extra-legal violence in support of community values before the select committee of the Senate.
And I knew that couldn't be hurting this.
We're about the same age.
He was looking at me and getting this great compliment and recognition of his expertise.
And we're talking about this great conversation.
So it was really good there.
But it was fun.
Way off the topic.
You get discharged.
When?
I got discharged on August the 13th.
of 46.
And back in school September of 46.
And so you're one of those, one of that large, large group of veterans.
9,000 students.
Compare what it was like to arrive in 46 with what it had been like to arrive in 44.
I was coming home.
I was coming home to A&M.
I felt very much
At home, okay.
I literally, while I left home in 44, I was coming, when I came to A&M, I was coming home in 46.
Were there many of the folks that you had been with in 44, were many of them back also?
Oh, yes, yes, yes, yes, yes, yes.
And what outfit were you in?
I was in a veteran's outfit.
I came back
I was a sophomore academically.
I signed up and got a contract in ROTC.
I was a junior in ROTC, and I had senior privileges.
All my classmates were seniors.
All the people who come into Fort Worth were, by now, because of the accelerated program, seniors.
So I was a senior.
So for three years, I was a senior at A&M.
But I never was a, with privilege, never was a sophomore or junior.
Freshman to senior.
So where were you assigned in terms of dormitories?
First I was in a veteran's outfit.
And where were you?
Then I went over on the core staff and joined the outfit of our classmate of mine, Country Higgins, football's four-year story, football was killed in Korea.
Where were you?
We were in the new area, the quad.
I moved from those two buildings right up on Duncan.
First semester I was over here.
Second semester I was
I mean, then I moved over to E Infantry and was in there.
But you were in a veteran's outfit, but you all still marched to chow?
No.
Oh, you didn't?
No.
What did you all wear?
I was saying we wore, I wore the pinks, just what seniors wore, except I never bought boots.
People didn't wear, the seniors didn't wear the boots in those days the way they do now.
Now, and nobody messed with you veterans?
No.
No pranks, no jokes?
No.
Nothing like that?
No, no.
Where did you all eat in the dining hall?
Did you eat as a unit?
Well, they changed everything by that time, too.
Because they had so many civilian veterans here, they had cafeteria style.
Oh, okay.
And I think I did that.
And the campus was crammed with people, wasn't it?
A campus.
The campus was crammed.
They had no campus housing.
They moved, they closed Bryan Air Force Base and put freshmen out there the next year, I guess.
And it was packed and they had to digest all these veterans.
And the married veterans lived...
They moved in some housing.
over there where the Hensel apartments are in that area there, made apartments out of old barracks as they moved in there.
They put in a lot of barracks.
I don't know if they did in the war, but they did, exactly.
And over South of the football field?
No.
Oh, no.
Over near the water tower?
Over near the water tower.
And where the engineer and where the physics, the cyclotron and all that is over in that area, generally speaking.
And also I took classes over there.
Now, did you and your fellow veteran buddies feel more mature?
We were more mature.
We were more mature.
When I came back, classroom work was like falling off a log.
First time, first time I came back, I was worried about it.
I wanted to do better than I'd done before.
I took 15 hours.
Monday, Wednesday, and Friday.
ROTC drill on Thursday afternoon.
Kept Saturday free as much as I could.
and wanted anything to it.
And so you made good grades.
Made good grades, twice, you know.
Who were some of the, you're a history major now.
History major.
And who were some of the history faculty?
Well, we had, and I'll use what we called, I don't know the first name, Screaming Al Nelson.
Wait, and describe why they had those nicknames.
Well, Screaming Al Nelson, Screaming, his first name was Al, A-L-A-L.
And you could hear him throughout the academic building when he was teaching.
And I did not have him for a lot of courses, maybe for one course.
But you could hear him all over the building.
And one of them did have Arshter Gaumann.
Now, Arshter because he .
They're teaching.
And he had a unique way of teaching that you had a reading assignment.
And you came in, and you'd sit there.
He'd ask a question and call somebody and make a mark in his thing, in his grade book of some kind, if you answered the question correctly or not.
And that's the way he talked.
I also had a Dr. Hill, who left here at the University of Texas, who was... John Hill.
Yeah.
In retrospect, a good American historian, and he was one that really challenged me, I thought.
Did you have Ralph Steen?
I had him, I think, for one course.
one semester for, I think it was a government course.
